If you need to improve shoulder external rotation, you'll likely look up someone cranking their shoulder backwards with a PVC pipe stretch like I'm showing at the start of this video. Now while there can be a time and place for this exercise in some situations, I rarely find this is an OPTIMAL choice for many. Too often this stretch is performed WAY TO AGGRESSIVELY and for the wrong person.❌ 
.
Most athletes do not lack shoulder external rotation because their JOINT needs to be stretched but because the larger muscles that attach to the shoulder and perform the movement of internal rotation are stiff/tight (lats and pecs specifically). This means doing some simple flexibility work with the pecs and lats can instantly improve external rotation. 
.
If you'd like to watch the rest of this video, including exercises to improve lat flexibility, check out the YouTube video "Back Squat Shoulder Mobility (Fix Your Rack Position)"📲

Here’s some behind the scenes rehab of a recent patient dealing with hip pain with squatting actions. This particular clip is of us working on the touchdown squat exercise. During the start of this exercise she had a small amount of pain, which was taken away with an RNT addition to the drill. 
.
This goes to show how her hip pain had a direct connection to the stability her hips need to make for more optimal movement. Is this a final fix? Not by itself - we also worked on banded joint mobilizations and other stability drills before this - BUT this is a key part of the full fix. Understanding how we can modify symptoms in real time, give access to new motion & allow for improved quality of movement is an essential part of the evaluation & rehabilitation program. Remember there is no one size fits all program for fixing any injury. It all comes down to a proper evaluation & individualizing our fixes based on what we find. 
.
Shout out to @joselynmiller90 for being my patient model for the day!

When someone asks “Are deadlifts good for low back pain rehab?” the answer is usually yes…but WHEN they are implanted is always “it depends!”
.
Today I’m sharing 2 patients of mine who both had pain with deadlifts and both had MRI scans that showed bulging discs. However the movement evaluation I performed (with many tests I learned first from renowned back expert @backfitpro) showed they had different triggers for their pain. For this reason, both could not tolerate deadlifting from the ground at the start of their rehab. This is why a “one size fits all approach” to rehab for any injury does NOT work. While both got back to deadlifting - their path was different.
.
Shout out @mrsc_boehm & @krispy_kremez for being my patient models for the day.
.
If you’re dealing with low back pain and want to learn what your movement diagnosis is, check out my blog “How to screen your low back pain” on Squatuniversity.com & the different case study videos on my YouTube channel.

I wanted to share with you guys a recent experience I had working with @nolanparke5. In trying to work through some technique issues we worked on different cues and found "spread the floor" to work much more than "screw the feet into the ground." 
.
I wanted to share this video with you guys for 2 reasons: 
1) Not all technique issues require specialized corrective exercises. As a coach, always see if we can fix movement faults with simple cues first. If that doesn't work THEN take the athlete aside and screen to figure out what may be at fault. 
2) There is no "golden rule" that works for everyone. Some cues work great for some athletes and have no change in others. It's all about finding what cue resonates and can facilitate the change you're looking for. 
.
Nolan is lifting on the @fitmap_trainer today, a great way to visualize technique problems!

There’s 2 parts to the banded joint mobilization. Let’s go over them.👇🏼
.
First, push the knee across the body while you RELAX the hip muscles. This is pushing into hip internal rotation. Now If this creates a pinch/block sensation in the front of the hip - get more tension on the band. Hold for a few seconds - you may get a light gapping sensation in your lateral hip. 
.
Second, push the knee out to the side and squeeze your glutes. This is driving active external rotation and re-educating your body to create this optimal lateral and posterior glute engagement during your lifts. Hold for a few seconds again.
.
Usually I have athletes/patients do 5-10 reps and then ALWAYS retest your squat to see how you’re moving after & assess whether this was a good exercise for you. 
.
As always, shout out to Dr. Kelly Starrett of @thereadystate from whom I first learned these from! 
.

Tempo work can be a game-changer for solidifying control of a movement. This slow descent squat for enhancing awareness of your positioning is a tip I first learned from the greatest powerlifter of all time @eddycoan

If you need to improve shoulder external rotation, you'll likely look up someone cranking their shoulder backwards with a PVC pipe stretch like I'm showing at the start of this video. Now while there can be a time and place for this exercise in some situations, I rarely find this is an OPTIMAL choice for many. Too often this stretch is performed WAY TO AGGRESSIVELY and for the wrong person.❌ 
.
Most athletes do not lack shoulder external rotation because their JOINT needs to be stretched but because the larger muscles that attach to the shoulder and perform the movement of internal rotation are stiff/tight (lats and pecs specifically). This means doing some simple flexibility work with the pecs and lats can instantly improve external rotation. 
.
If you'd like to watch the rest of this video, including exercises to improve lat flexibility, check out the YouTube video "Back Squat Shoulder Mobility (Fix Your Rack Position)"📲

Today’s society sells you “secret programs, hacks & inside scoops” to gaining strength, hitting that next PR or sculpting that perfect physique. In reality, none of these are found overnight. There is no ultimate 8-week program that will bring you to elite status or make all your lifting dreams come true. But that’s not what you want to hear. It’s not sexy & telling you that true strength is built on top of consistent hard work day in and day out for YEARS doesn’t sell...but it’s true.🤯
.
If you put 100 lbs on your squat after an 8 week program - great - but that happened because you’re still a beginner & you have much further to go. True strength isn’t built over a few weeks, a few months or even a few years. It’s when consistency & hard work meet and are cultivated over YEARS ... that’s where the magic happens.🏋🏼‍♂️
.
Set short term & long term goals. Stay consistent & learn to love THE PROCESS of working towards your goals.🙌🏼

While Ive said plenty of times, the basic fundamental lifts in the gym are “core” stability drills if done with the right emphasis … that doesn’t mean assistant core exercises have no value. For example, This is the pallof press with an eventual lateral walk exercise. The goal with each part is to brace the core and resist any twisting of the spine. This would categorize this type of movement as anti-rotation and it would be helpful for improving stability to limit problems like this when the lift is received a bit off balance. 
.
If you think about it, most lifts within the gym are within a vertical or horizontal plane of motion. Sometimes athletes will develop imbalances that lead to instability within a rotational plane of motion but not realize it until it leads to larger movement issues. This type of drill can therefore be a missing “piece of the pie” to help enhance an athletes stability & build a “core of iron” like @briancarroll1306 likes to say!
.
Shout out to @luxiaojunbarbell for being today’s athlete model, his physio @mohamedkine1 for guiding Lu with this excellent drill & to @3d4medical with the Complete Anatomy app for the visual of the body!

node.text:
When you look at the research, there is actually a very LOW risk of injury to children who participate in weightlifting! For example, one research study followed a group of youth competitive weightlifters over an entire year of training and competing. After a full year, there was not a single injury found that limited training or required professional medical attention. (Byrd R, Pierce K, Reilly L, Brady J. Young weightlifters’ performance across time. Sports Biomechanics. 2003;2:133-140).
.
Young athletes can even find their 1 repetition maximum (1RM) without fear of injury (provided proper technique and supervision). Don’t believe me? Read these articles:
.
1. Hetzler R, DeRenne C, Buxton B, et al. Effects of 12 weeks of strength training on anaerobic power in prepubescent male athletes. J Strength Cond Res 1997;11:174-81
.
2. Faigenbaum AD, Milliken LA, Westcott WL. Maximal strength testing in healthy children. J Strength Cond Res. 2003;17:162-6.
.
The force an athlete sustains when performing a maximal strength test (such as a 1 RM squat) is actually less than what they would be exposed to on a daily basis in most other sports (Faigenbaum AD, & Myer GD. Resistance training among young athletes: safety, efficacy and injury prevention effects. Br J Sports Med. 2010 Jan;44(1):56-63.)
.
What about growth plates? While it is true maturing bones can be 2-5 times weaker than the surrounding tissues barbell training, however, is not one of the leading causes of growth plate injuries to children. The leading causes include American football, followed closely by baseball, gymnastics and hockey (Caine D, DiFiori J, Maffulli N. Physeal injuries in children’s and youth sports: reasons for concern? BJSM. March 2014;749-60).
.
Stunted growth? Nope…there has never been any scientific evidence that youth weight training is harmful to the normal growth and development process (Malina R. Weight training in youth – growth, maturation and safety: an evidenced based review. Clin J Sports Med. 2006;16:478-87.)
.

I’m always working to clean up my own technique & become a better lifter myself. After Olympic lifting for over 16 years I still love the challenge of always trying to get one step better. Here’s a recent double at 80 kg. Not a PR lift but that’s not everyday training. It’s the technique work & attention to detail with day to day lifting at non max weights that make the big lifts move easier when the time comes to lift them. 
.
Big shout out to my coach @olychad for all his help in programming and helping me chip away at perfecting my own technique too! Remember, even coaches need coaches!

Do you sit in a deep squat during the day (outside of your workout)??? If so, how often & for how long?
.
This post goes along the theme of what Gray Cook of @functionalmvmt always says “Move well & move often.” Remember, the squat is a movement ever before it’s an exercise. Unfortunately our society has conceptually rearranged our idea of the squat to think it is only something to do a few times a week with a weight at the gym. When you flip this paradigm back in place & start working the squat into your daily movement habits good things happen.

node.text:
Do you notice a twist in the descent portion of your squat? I find this is often due to a difference in side to side mobility of either the hip joint or ankle joint.📝👇🏼
.
1️⃣ A great active warm up shown here by @max_lang_weightlifting helps promote hip internal rotation. A restriction in this rotation on one side will cause your body to twist away from that hip, keeping it in external rotation in order to avoid the blockage.🤯
.
2️⃣ You can then sit in your deep bodyweight squat and actively drive your knees out to the side. Make sure your feet stay firmly panted to the ground with your big toe jammed down to make sure your feet don’t roll on their side. Feel for whether or not you’re able to move your legs equally out to the side.✅
.
3️⃣Now, if the mobility restriction is lower at the ankle we can work on fixing that with either stretching (by jumping on a box and driving your knee over your toes for a hold) or doing banded joint mobilizations (if you have a pinch or blocked sensation in the front of your ankle)✅ This mobility restriction will limit knee over toe translation, causing you to twist toward the non-restricted side.
.
Make sure to re-screen your squat after these mobilty tools to find out if they are right for your body!🙌🏼
.
Thank you to @3d4medical & their app Complete Anatomy for the body visual today 🙏🏼

Here’s some behind the scenes rehab of a recent patient dealing with hip pain with squatting actions. This particular clip is of us working on the touchdown squat exercise. During the start of this exercise she had a small amount of pain, which was taken away with an RNT addition to the drill. 
.
This goes to show how her hip pain had a direct connection to the stability her hips need to make for more optimal movement. Is this a final fix? Not by itself - we also worked on banded joint mobilizations and other stability drills before this - BUT this is a key part of the full fix. Understanding how we can modify symptoms in real time, give access to new motion & allow for improved quality of movement is an essential part of the evaluation & rehabilitation program. Remember there is no one size fits all program for fixing any injury. It all comes down to a proper evaluation & individualizing our fixes based on what we find. 
.
Shout out to @joselynmiller90 for being my patient model for the day!

If you have uneven elbows in a front rack position, it’s often due to 2 problems.👇🏼
.
The first is due to a side to side flexibility difference in your lats. If tighter on one side it will limit how high you can raise your elbows for your front rack. A helpful drill is an eccentric curl up taking 5 seconds to lower back down. This eccentrically lengthens the lat muscles under load to improve flexibility. I usually will have people do 5 reps to start.
.
Anther cause may be limited protraction of your shoulder blade – potentially due to a weak or under facilitated serratus anterior muscle. A helpful drill is an upside down kettlebell walk with the cue to drive your elbow forward in the rack position while you then walk. As always be sure to recheck your rack position to see if WHAT you did allowed for better movement quality in the end. 
.
